<subSubSection pageId="109" pageNumber="110" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="109.[151,1437,762,1725]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1663,1689]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zahniser" authorityYear="2021" box="[324,449,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Tenucephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="johnsoni">
<emphasis box="[324,449,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">T. johnsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar and related to the distantly located 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zahniser" authorityYear="2021" box="[1169,1310,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Tenucephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lingulatus">
<emphasis box="[1169,1310,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">T. lingulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingRegion country="Peru" name="Madre de Dios" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Madre de Dios</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[218,274,1699,1725]" name="Peru" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Peru</collectingCountry>
). The two species were resolved with strong branch support in a clade with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zahniser" authorityYear="2021" box="[1122,1239,1699,1725]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Tenucephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bartletti">
<emphasis box="[1122,1239,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">T. bartletti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1255,1338,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGUIRE 91" captionStartId="145.[151,259,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[193,1386,191,1829]" captionTargetId="figure-16@145.[193,1394,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="145" captionText="FIGUIRE 91. Strict consensus tree from MP analysis of 51 morphological characters. Numbers below branches are MP bootstrap scores. The plesiomorphic condition is macroptery for both males and females (Hecalocorica bidentata ♂ shown in up- per left). Key stepwise transitions leading to brachyptery occur on clades A (char. 20; forewing of Hecullus bracteatus ♀ and hindwing of Acrolithus brevis ♀ shown), B (char. 22; Acrolithus brevis ♂ shown), and C (chars. 20 &amp; 22; Dietrichana pampas ♀ shown)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4691039" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4691039/files/figure.png" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Fig. 91</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
